{{Infobox power station | name = KCHT Power Station | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = | country = Sri Lanka | location = [[Muthurajawela]] | status = U | construction_began = 10 August 2017 | commissioned = 2019 | decommissioned = | cost = [[United States dollar|US$]]95 million | owner = {{Nowrap|KCHT Holding}}, [[Seoul]] | operator = {{Nowrap|KCHT Lanka Jang (Pvt) Ltd}} | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | ps_thermal_capacity = | ps_heating_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = 10 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_storage_hours = | ps_annual_generation = | ps_annual_gen_year = | website = http://www.kchtholding.com/en/project.html | extra = }}
The '''KCHT Power Station''' is a [[municipal solid waste]]-fired [[thermal power station]] currently under construction at [[Muthurajawela]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. It is being constructed together with the [[Aitken Spence Power Station]], after it won the bid by the [[Ministry of Urban Development (Sri Lanka)|Urban Development Authority]] from a pool of 121 bidders, 19 of which were foreign. Construction of the facility began on {{Nowrap|10 August 2017}} and will cost approximately {{Nowrap|[[United States dollar|US$]]95 million}}, with an estimated completion slated for mid-2019.<ref name="DailyFT">{{cite news|title=Two waste-to-energy plants to get off the ground today|url=http://www.ft.lk/article/634380/Two-waste-to-energy-plants-to-get-off-the-ground-today|accessdate=8 October 2017|publisher=[[Daily FT]]|date=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="LBO">{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka to kick off solid waste plants with USD193 mln investment|url=http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/sri-lanka-to-kick-off-solid-waste-plants-with-usd193-mln-investment/|accessdate=8 October 2017|work=[[Lanka Business Online]]|date=10 August 2017}}</ref>
The {{Nowrap|10 [[megawatt]]}} power station will be operated by {{Nowrap|KCHT Lanka Jang (Private) Limited}}, a subsidiary of the [[South Korea|South Korean]] company {{Nowrap|KCHT Holding}}. It will use {{Convert|630|MT|lb|lk=on}} of waste from the [[Colombo]] and [[Gampaha]] suburbs. The generated power will be sold to the state-owned [[Ceylon Electricity Board]] at a rate of {{Nowrap|[[Sri Lankan rupee|Rs]]. 37.10 per [[KWh]]}} generated. The remaining [[bottom ash]] resulting from the process would be used for [[road construction]] and other purposes, while the unusable [[fly ash]] residue (amounting to 2%) being disposed at locations already identified.<ref name="DailyFT" /> {{Clear}}
