[[File:Stele of Meli-Šipak.jpg|thumb|420px|The Stele of Meli-Šipak identified by a colophon provided by Ellamite king Šutruk-Naḫḫunte.]]

The '''Stele of Meli-Šipak''' is an ancient [[Mesopotamian]] fragment of the bottom part of a large rectangular stone edifice engraved with reliefs and the remains of [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] and [[Elamite language|Elamite]] inscriptions. It was taken as spoil of war by [[Elam]]ite king [[Shutruk-Nakhunte|Šutruk-Naḫḫunte I]] during his invasion of [[Babylonia]] which deposed [[Kassites|Kassite]] king [[Zababa-shuma-iddin|Zababa-šuma-iddina]]. It was one of the objects found at [[Susa]] between 1900 and 1904 by the French excavation team under [[Jacques de Morgan]] that seems to have formed part of an ancient Museum of trophies, or ''ex-voto'' offerings to the deity [[Inshushinak|Inšušinak]], in a courtyard adjacent to the main temple.<ref>{{ cite journal | title = Classification, Historiography and Monumental Authority: the Babylonian Entitlement Narûs (Kudurrus) | author = Kathryn E. Slanski | journal = JCS | volume = 52 | year = 2000 | page = 96 }}</ref>

==The stele==

The limestone stele is engraved with towers, crowning battlements and separating a crenelated wall fortification below, where there is an archway in the lower of perhaps three [[register (sculpture)|register]]s. At least one row of divine symbols appears in an upper register. A human figure dressed in an ornate fringed robe and a high crown of feathers, faces a ship. A standing nude figure has been intentionally chiseled away.<ref name=seidl>{{ cite book | title = Die Babylonischen Kudurru-Reliefs: Symbole Mesopotamischer Gottheiten | author = Ursula Seidl | publisher = Academic Press Fribourg | year = 1989 | pages = 31–32 }}</ref> 

The object was first published by [[Jean-Vincent Scheil]] in 1902<ref>{{ cite book | title = Mémoires de la Délégation en Perse, Tome IV: Textes Élamites - Sémitiques | author = V. Scheil | location = Paris | year = 1902 | pages = 163–165 }}</ref> and is currently kept in the [[Musée du Louvre]] in Paris, with excavation reference Sb 14 and Museum reference AS 6049. It is the [[colophon (publishing)|colophon]] added by Šutruk-Naḫḫunte (one of several, but which is very similar to that inscribed on the [[Naram-Sin of Akkad#Victory_stele|Victory stele of Narām-Sîn]]<ref>{{ cite book | title = Die einheimischen Quellen zur Geschichte Elams, Volume 1 | author = Georg Hüsing | publisher = J.C. Hinrichs | year = 1916 | pages = 52–53 }}</ref>), written perpendicular to the Middle Babylonian cuneiform and up one of the carved towers, which identifies it as an artifact of [[Meli-Shipak II|Meli-Šipak]], as the remnants of the original inscription do not provide any historical information:

{{quote|I (am) Šutruk-Naḫ[ḫunte, the son] of [Ḫalluduš-Inšušin]ak, the beloved servant [of (the god) Inšušinak], the king of Anzan [(and) Susa, the enlarge]er of [my realm, the caretaker of Elam, [the prince of Elam].As Inšušinak, [my god, instr]uct[ed me, I smote] (the land) Karintaš. [I] acquired the stele of Meli-[Šipak] in Kari[ntaš] [(and brought it to Elam)].<ref name=slanski>{{ cite book | title = The Babylonian Entitlement narûs (kudurrus): A Study in Their Form and Function | author = Kathryn E. Slanski | publisher = ASOR | year = 2003 | pages = 194–196 }}</ref>}}

The royal name preserved is given by Brinkman as <sup>m</sup>˹''Me-''x˺ [   ] which he described as providing “little support for such an interpretation”<ref name=brinkman>{{ cite book | title = Materials and Studies for Kassite History, Vol. I (MSKH I) | chapter = * Meli-Šipak | author = J. A. Brinkman | publisher = Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago | year = 1976 | page = 258 }} S.5.1.</ref> while Slanski observed that the faint traces following ˹''Me''˺ conform rather well to the sign ''–li-''. Little more of the text other than the tail end of the curse formula is preserved:

{{quote|[Gula, mistress of] the gods, may she afflict him with her oozing (sores), a persistent carbuncle, so that he may bathe in blood and pus like water!<ref name=slanski/>}}

This is reminiscent of the curses which appear on column seven of the [[Melišipak kudurru-Land grant to Marduk-apal-iddina I|Land grant to Marduk-apal-iddina I kudurru]], and provides the main reason for identifying this object within the genre of kudurrus, the Babylonian entitlement ''narûs''.<ref name=seidl/>

