The '''Super-iron battery''' is a moniker for a proposed class of rechargeable [[battery (electricity)|electric battery]]. Such batteries feature cathodes composed of [[ferrate]] salts, either [[potassium ferrate]] ({{chem|K|2|FeO|4}}) or [[barium ferrate]] ({{chem|BaFeO|4}}).<ref>Licht, S.; R. Tel-Vered "Rechargeable Fe(III/VI) super-iron cathodes" ''Chemical Communications'', 2004, volume 6, p.&nbsp;628-629. {{doi|10.1039/b400251b}}</ref> One attraction to the proposed device is that the spent cathode would consist of a [[rust]]-like material, which is preferable to batteries based on [[cadmium]], [[manganese]] and [[nickel]].
